# name: thyroid hormone binding (GO:0070324) # def: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with thyroxine (T4) or triiodothyronine (T3), tyrosine-based hormones produced by the thyroid gland. [['GOC:rph']] # synonyms: thyroxine binding:NARROW triiodothyronine binding:NARROW

# name: Hemostasis impairing toxin (KW-1199) # def: Toxin which interferes with hemostasis regrouping all mechanisms implicated in the cessation of blood loss through damaged vessels Hence, hemostasis impairing toxins not only interfere with platelet aggregation, the coagulation cascade, fibrinogen depletion, and fibrin clot degradation (fibrinolysis), but also provoke hemorrhage by damaging endothelial cells or disturbing their interaction with the basement membrane. Numerous snake venom families have the capacity to interfere with hemostasis #

# name: Thiol protease inhibitor (KW-0789) # def: Protein which inhibits the activity of a thiol protease, a class of proteases that contains an active site cysteine residue (Cys), e.g papain, cathepsins, etc # synonyms: Thiol peptidase inhibitor Thiol proteinase inhibitor

# name: cysteine-type endopeptidase inhibitor activity (GO:0004869) # def: Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a cysteine-type endopeptidase, any enzyme that hydrolyzes peptide bonds in polypeptides by a mechanism in which the sulfhydryl group of a cysteine residue at the active center acts as a nucleophile. [['GOC:dph', 'GOC:tb']] # synonyms: cystatin:NARROW cysteine protease inhibitor activity:NARROW thiol protease inhibitor:NARROW

a.xlink:title: # name: tRNA-binding (KW-0820) # def: Protein which binds transfer RNA, for example some ribosomal proteins or some aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases # synonyms: Transfer RNA binding

# name: Antioxidant (KW-0049) # def: Protein capable of counteracting the damaging effects of oxidation, e.g. by trapping free radicals generated during the metabolic burst and possibly inhibiting ageing. Scavengers of highly reactive and harmful oxygen species #

# name: Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase (KW-0030) # def: Enzyme that activates an amino acid for translation by forming an aminoacyladenylate intermediate and then links this activated amino acid to the corresponding tRNA molecule (amino acid-tRNA, aminoacyl- tRNA). In general, a specific aminoacyl-tRNA synthase is available for each amino acid # synonyms: Amino acid translase Aminoacyl-tRNA ligase Aminoacyl-tRNA synthase

# name: Chloride channel (KW-0869) # def: Protein which is part of an anion channel found in the plasma membrane and in intracellular membranes. These channels are permeable for various anions, such as iodide, bromide, but also for nitrates, phosphates and even negatively charged amino acids. They are called chloride channels, because chloride is the most abundant anion and the predominant permeating species in all organisms. They have been classified according to their gating mechanisms, which may depend on changes in the transmembrane electric field (voltage-dependent/gated chloride channels, e.g. ClC family), on a protein kinase/nucleotide mediated mechanism (CFTR), an increase in intracellular calcium (calcium activated chloride channels, e.g. CaCC), cell swelling (volume-regulated anion channels, e.g. VRAC) or binding of a ligand, e.g. glycine or - aminobutyric acid (GABA) activated channels. In contrast with cation channels, they are not involved in the initiation or spread of excitation, but in the regulation of excitability in nerve and muscle. They also participate in many housekeeping processes, such as volume regulation, pH regulation in organelles, electrogenesis and control of synaptic activity. The chloride channels are crucial for transepithelial transport and the control of water flow, and often provide unexpected permeation pathways for a large variety of anions # synonyms: Chloride anion channel Chloride ion channel Cl- channel
# name: Excision nuclease (KW-0267) # def: Enzyme which excises abnormal or mismatched nucleotides from a DNA strand #

# name: Monoclonal antibody (KW-0502) # def: Antibody produced by a single clone of B cells and thus consisting of a population of identical antibody molecules all specicfic for a single antigenic determinant. They are produced from cultured hybridoma cell lines for research and commercial purposes #
# name: Dermonecrotic toxin (KW-1061) # def: Protein involved in the necrosis of the skin #

# name: Complement system impairing toxin (KW-1216) # def: Toxin which interferes with the complement system. These toxins act by activating, inhibiting, or mimicking proteins of this system. They are mostly found in snake and spider venoms #

g.title: Complement system impairing toxin->phospholipase D activity

a.xlink:title: # name: Chaperone (KW-0143) # def: Protein which is transiently involved in the noncovalent folding, assembly and/or disassembly of other polypeptides or RNA molecules, including any transport and oligomerisation processes they may undergo, and the refolding and reassembly of protein and RNA molecules denatured by stress. Though involved in these processes, chaperones are not an integral part of these functioning molecules. Also used for metallochaperones, which function to provide a metal directly to target proteins while protecting this metal from scavengers #

# name: Milk protein (KW-0494) # def: Protein found in milk, a fluid secreted by female mammals to provide food for their offspring. It consists of water, proteins, soluble carbohydrates, electrolytes, lipids and vitamins #

# name: Bence-Jones protein (KW-0086) # def: Protein which is a dimer of immunoglobulin light chains synthesized in large amounts by patients who have myeloma or bone marrow tumor Bence-Jones protein is sufficiently small to be excreted by the kidney into urine #
# name: Presynaptic neurotoxin (KW-0638) # def: Protein which acts as a neurotoxin at the presynaptic membrane and usually blocks neuromuscular transmission #

# name: Blood coagulation cascade inhibiting toxin (KW-1203) # def: Toxin which inhibits the blood coagulation cascade, which leads to the production of fibrin clots. Blood coagulation inhibiting toxins include a variety of snake venom proteases #

g.title: Blood coagulation cascade inhibiting toxin->phospholipase A2 activity

a.xlink:title: # name: Cell adhesion impairing toxin (KW-1217) # def: Toxin which interferes with the adherence of cells to other cells or to a matrix. Cell adhesion impairing toxins are mostly found in venom of snakes #

# name: Platelet aggregation inhibiting toxin (KW-1201) # def: Toxin which inhibits agonist-induced platelet aggregation, the self- adhesion of platelets via adhesion molecules. Numerous snake venom families have the capacity to inhibit platelet aggregation #

g.title: Platelet aggregation inhibiting toxin->phospholipase A2 activity

a.xlink:title: # name: Myotoxin (KW-0959) # def: Protein which causes muscle necrosis. Myotoxins are principally found in snake venoms. The myotoxic activity can be monitored by morphological analysis and by the increase of plasma creatine kinase (CK) activity. The increase in plasma CK levels results from sarcolemmal damage due to myotoxic components of the venom #

# name: Hemorrhagic toxin (KW-1200) # def: Toxin which induces the leakage of blood components into tissues by damaging endothelial cells or disturbing endothelial cell interactions with the basement membrane. Hemorrhagic toxins are mostly found in snake venoms # synonyms: Hemorrhagin

# name: Fibrinogenolytic toxin (KW-1206) # def: Toxin involved in fibrinogen degradation leading to a decrease of plasma fibrinogen concentration. Fibrinogenolytic toxins are mostly snake venom proteases #
# name: Postsynaptic neurotoxin (KW-0629) # def: Protein which acts as a neurotoxin at the postsynaptic membrane. They bind to acetylcholine receptors and so inhibit their activity #
# name: Viral movement protein (KW-0916) # def: Plant viral protein that enables the viral nucleic acid to move between adjacent plant cells via the plasmodesmata #

# name: Voltage-gated potassium channel impairing toxin (KW-1220) # def: Protein which interferes with the function of voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv) which are membrane proteins forming a channel in a biological membrane selectively permeable to potassium ions and open in response to a change in membrane potential. They are mostly found in scorpion and spider venoms #

g.title: Voltage-gated potassium channel impairing toxin->serine-type endopeptidase inhibitor activity

a.xlink:title: # name: Pathogenesis-related protein (KW-0568) # def: Protein induced in several plant species when they are infected by viruses, viroids, fungi or bacteria. The occurrence of these proteins is not pathogen-specific, but determined by the type of reaction of the host plant. They form a protective barrier against pathogens by collecting at infection sites and act to decrease susceptibility of plants. They may have anti-fungal or anti-bacterial activity # synonyms: PR protein
